<section id="directions-for-future-research-and-design">
<p id="role-of-authentication-capabilities">Used WebID-TLS first.. and then had to adopt to WebID-OIDC. Decentralised authentication mechanisms is vital.</p>

<p id="privacy-aware-information-space"><strong>Privacy Aware Information Spaces</strong>: Actors can better make decisions if their applications are privacy-aware, for example through ODRLs.. We should also observe the interplay of forces and functions in scholarly communication to see how privacy-aware applications may materialise new forms of content and interactions.</p>
</section>

<p>Designing other RACA-Aware decentralised applications.. how can we remix specs to address other/new problems?</p>

<p> What has it shaped? What are the current challenges? How do we envision the communication to be? How can we use the medium better whether through its original intentions or new?</p>

<p>Personal On-Demand Archiving Services. Storage?</p>

<p>browsers should be Linked Data aware to enable smarter applications. right now each application has to include LD-know-how to take more advantage of the Web. if browsers natively supported those features, we can create advance the quality of applications.</p>

<p>We can indeed navigate through specific units of information as well as search and query.</p>

              <p id="third-parties-considered-harmful"><strong>Third-Parties Considered Harmful</strong>: What the overarching technical research problem..
              "Third-party" publishers are not required. If anything, generally limits or has constraints on what and how Web resources can be published.

In light of existing scholarly publishing practices, I contend that third-party publishers are not required especially in context of the Web. After all, on the Web, anyone can technically be a publisher. This, the social conventions that surrounds the notion of a scholarly contribution should be revisited.
              </p>
